ment-image\" data-media-id=\"6ce82c654d2a21627b11c8bf146af4a66d4170c7\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/6ce82c654d2a21627b11c8bf146af4a66d4170c7/0_0_3000_1800/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Sharon Stone attends the amfAR’s Inspiration Gala Los Angeles.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sharon Stone attends the amfAR’s Inspiration Gala Los Angeles. ‘By bemoaning the dent that being female has effected in their multi-million pound pay packets, actresses are merely perpetuating the notion that feminism is bourgeois and out of touch,’ says Matilda Embling.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Valerie Macon/AFP/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6ce82c654d2a21627b11c8bf146af4a66d4170c7/0_0_3000_1800/140.jpg","body":"<p>I wish Hollywood’s women would use their public influence to talk about the rest of us (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/nov/09/sharon-stone-after-basic-instinct-no-one-wanted-to-pay-me\" title=\"\">Sharon Stone: my tears over Hollywood’s gender pay gap, 10 November</a>). Now Kate Winslet reveals that she finds the entire conversation “vulgar” (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/nov/11/kate-winslet-the-gender-pay-gap-debate-is-a-bit-vulgar\" title=\"\">Report, 11 November</a>). In some ways I agree with her, but my reasoning is different. I do believe it is despicable that actresses get paid so much less than their male counterparts and that this is an issue that deserves to be addressed. However, it does perturb me that women with such sway over the public conscience and such ability to raise awareness and effect change, use this power to discuss their own pay packets.</p> <p>Most of the actresses who have vocally denounced the gender pay gap could probably afford to lose a zero from their annual salary before having to give up their house or one of their cars. I understand this is not the point; men are getting paid more to do the same job. However, I wish they would use those moments, when the entire world is hanging on their every word, to talk about the women whose homes are put in jeopardy by the loss of a mere £20 a week. I believe that gender equality in every sense will come from below, not above. By bemoaning the dent that being female has effected in their multimillion-pound pay packets, actresses are merely perpetuating the notion that feminism is both bourgeois and out of touch. <br /><strong>Matilda Embling</strong><br /><em>London </em></p> <p>• This year’s Equal Pay Day fell on 9 November – marking the moment from which women are now working for free (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/09/gender-pay-gap-women-working-free-until-end-of-year\" title=\"\">Report, 9 November</a>). However, young women on apprenticeships have been working for free since 28 October, almost two weeks earlier (based on a similar calculation), because they earn 21% less than their male counterparts. The gender pay gap debate has focused on women over 40 in the professional world. But equal attention needs to be given to younger women, often in low-paid work, at the beginning of their careers.<br /><strong>Dr Carole Easton</strong><br /><em>Chief executive, Young Women’s Trust</em></p> <p>• Polly Toynbee cites a shocking High Pay Centre report which reveals that the average salary of chief executives is now £5m (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/03/joy-tax-scandanavian-services-us-tax-rates\" title=\"\">Report, 3 November</a>). So why, according to the CBI leader, John Cridland, will many employers be unable to afford a living wage of £9 per hour by 2020 (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/03/national-living-wage-a-gamble-says-cbi-boss\" title=\"\">Report, 3 November</a>)?<br /><strong>Pete Dorey</strong><br /><em>Bath, Somerset</em></p> <p><strong><em>• Join the debate – email </e