’s visit </em><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/11/on-his-uk-visit-narendra-modi-must-be-held-accountable-for-his-record-on-human-rights-in-india\" title=\"\"><em>here</em></a></p> <p>• The nation is now richer by owning a Van Dyck painting (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/nov/09/bowes-museum-van-dyck-portrait-major-acquisition-for-north\" title=\"\">Going public, 10 November</a>). This gift defrays £2.4m of the Duke of Northumberland’s inheritance tax bill. Thanks Duke. Actually, we’d rather have had the money. It would have stretched a long way in struggling NHS hospitals. It could have built loads of new homes. Tax is levied to support the infrastructure of our society, to make it a good place to live; and the most privileged are, reasonably, asked to contribute proportionately more. <br /><strong>Barbara Crowther</strong><br /><em>Leamington, Warwickshire</em></p> <p>• TP Leary (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/06/heres-robot-peston-we-could-easily-automate-newsreaders\" title=\"\">Letters, 7 November</a>) scorns Lewes’s claim to be the biggest 5 November event in the world with the question, how many other countries celebrate Guy Fawkes? The answer is Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and the Caribbean. It’s a night whose stand for democracy over terror is seeing it win back adherence over the bland commercialism of Halloween. <br /><strong>Leo Schulz</strong><br /><em>London</em></p> <p>• My Bayko building set in the 1930s gave me hours of enjoyment (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/10/bayko-what-about-arkitex-office-blocks\" title=\"\">Letters, 11 November</a>). But from a safety point of view, the board with holes into which were slotted metal rods was lethal if left on a floor with children running around. It had to evolve into something safer.<br /><strong>Shirley Reed</strong><br /><em>Stanley, Durham</em></p> <p>• Alan Evans (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/global/2015/nov/08/why-the-british-are-not-spooked-by-spies\" title=\"\">Letters, 9 November)</a> seems to suggest totally terminating the two-word term thread. How about just rowing back instead?<br /><strong>Chris Baker</strong><br /><em>Minety, Wiltshire</em></p> <p><strong><em>• Join the debate – email </em></strong><a href=\"mailto:guardian.letters@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong><em>guardian.letters@theguardian.com</em></strong></a></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10969821","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405603","internalRevision":"16","internalContentCode":"458371382","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"<strong>Letters:</strong> How many other countries celebrate Guy Fawkes? The answer is Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and the Caribbean","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Worldwide where it’s Fawkes that counts","byline":"Letters","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T19:42:44Z","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447269620566/Bonfire-night-celebration-001.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"56439404e4b0560d979936e3","newspaperPageNumber":"44","creationDate":"2015-11-11T19:16:20Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-11T22:00:56.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/nov/11/worldwide-where-its-fawkes-that-counts","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/2015/nov/11/worldwide-where-its-fawkes-that-counts","sectionName":"Life and style","elements":[{"id":"5afd31c5fa2e866f8036bda7210d47d39100ae8d","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447269625618/Bonfire-night-celebration-005.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*32321791","suppliersReference":"LON107","altText":"Bonfire night celebrat