":"GD*51018234","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","suppliersReference":"E2DCK9","altText":"Ridley Road market, Hackney","source":"Alamy","mediaId":"9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","displayCredit":"true","credit":"Photograph: Alamy","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013/0_0_3776_2266/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013/0_0_3776_2266/3776.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Kathy deWitt / Alamy","picdarUrn":"GD*51018234","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","suppliersReference":"E2DCK9","altText":"Ridley Road market, Hackney","source":"Alamy","mediaId":"9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","displayCredit":"true","credit":"Photograph: Alamy","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013/0_0_3776_2266/3776.jpg","width":"3776","height":"2266"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013/0_0_3776_2266/master/3776.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Kathy deWitt / Alamy","picdarUrn":"GD*51018234","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","suppliersReference":"E2DCK9","altText":"Ridley Road market, Hackney","source":"Alamy","mediaId":"9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013","displayCredit":"true","credit":"Photograph: Alamy","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9118bb833a213c67a64596eecff89cfa3ed73013/0_0_3776_2266/master/3776.jpg","width":"3776","height":"2266","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/commentanddebate","webTitle":"Comment & debate","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/commentanddebate","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/commentanddebate","sectionName":"From the Guardian"}]},{"id":"world/2015/nov/11/rock-star-reception-visit-indian-prime-minister-narendra-modi","type":"article","sectionId":"world","webTitle":"Rock star reception lined up for visit of Indian prime minister Narendra Modi","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T11:02:52Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1513","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e28v","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"b97b08708818aa7387b8c23608f5c58bdd51db04\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/b97b08708818aa7387b8c23608f5c58bdd51db04/304_300_2610_1566/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Narendra Modi, who until three years ago was banned from the UK.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Narendra Modi, who until three years ago was banned from the UK.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Danish Ismail/Reuters/Corbis</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/b97b08708818aa7387b8c23608f5c58bdd51db04/304_300_2610_1566/140.jpg","body":"<p>Two packed coaches will be coming from the <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theicca.co.uk/\">Indian Community Centre Association in Nottingham</a>, according to its former chair Sudheer Gupta, “but there are lots of people going by their own transport as well. People are very excited. There are a lot of us who want to go and listen to what he has to say.”</p> <p>When Gupta and his colleagues set off on Friday they will be just one of many hundreds of delegations from around the UK <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"https://www.ukwelcomesmodi.org/\">converging on Wembley stadium</a> to greet <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/narendra-modi\">Narendra Modi</a>, the prime minister of <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/india\">India</a>, in the largest and arguably the most spectacular welcome any foreign leader has ever received in Britain.</p> <p>In total, 60,000 British Indians from <a href=\"https://www.ukwelcomesmodi.org/partners\">450 different community groups</a> – Hindu, Muslim, Sikh and others – are expected to pack into the national sports stadium to witness a rock star reception modelled on the Olympic opening ceremony, and almost matching it in ambition. Modi will be preceded at the free concert by an arts programme featuring 800 performers, including the Indian singing star Kanika Kapoor and the London Philharmonic Orchestra, and his address, coinciding with the festival of Diwali, will be followed by what is billed as one of the UK’s largest ever firework displays. </p> <p>Unlike the Chinese president <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/xi-jinping\">Xi Jinping</a>’s London visit in October, Modi’s trip to the UK is not a formal state visit, but the scale of the welcome being prepared for the 65-year-old is illustrative of his importance both to the huge Indian diaspora and to Britain as a whole. Modi will lunch with the Queen during his trip and is the first Indian prime minister ever to be invited to address both houses of parliament. During a packed three-day programme he will visit Indian businesses in the UK and stay a night at Chequers hosted by David Cameron. </p> <p>And though the Wembley concert is not an official event – it is being funded by <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"https://www.ukwelcomesmodi.org/#about-us\">Europe India Forum</a>, a non-profit company formed for the purpose by the multimillionaire British-Indian industrialist <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"https://www.lsbu.ac.uk/about-us/people-finder/prof-nathu-puri\">Nat Puri</a>, as well as corporate sponsors and thousands of individual donations – he will be introduced on stage by Cameron.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3bc6219b3dbef482c44aa7e87072789ef8ea626b\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3bc6219b3dbef482c44aa7e87072789ef8ea626b/174_197_3993_2397/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Narendra Modi.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Modi was state governor when riots left 1,000 Muslims dead.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Stephane de Sakutin/AFP/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>It represents a remarkable turnaround for a man who, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/oct/22/uk-ends-boycott-narendra-modi\">until three years ago</a>, had been banned for a decade from entering Britain, the US and several other European countries, following riots in Gujarat in 2002 in which 1,000 Muslims were killed by Hindu mobs. Modi, a Hindu nationalist who was state governor at the time, denied any involvement in the riots but was criticised for failing to do more to stop them. </p> <p>After Modi’s landslide election in 2014 as leader of the world’s biggest democracy (and now one of its fastest growing economies), the one-time pariah swiftly became a favoured partner, wooed by world leaders from Washington to Berlin to Beijing. <br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p> <p>Cameron has been eager to secure a slice of India’s economic boom for Britain, and has said he would like the UK to become India’s <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21495635\">“partner of choice”</a>. The employment minister, Priti Patel, <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/pm-modis-visit-to-boost-special-relationship-of-india-uk-priti-patel/\">described Modi’s forthcoming visit</a> as a chance for the two countries to take their “special relationship into the modern context”.</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/intrel/people/index.php/cco2.html\">Chris Ogden</a>, senior lecturer in Asian security at the University of St Andrews and the author of a book on Modi’s Bharatiya Janata party, said: “The big difference between then and now is that Modi is prime minister, so when he meets leaders from other countries, they are less inclined to criticise him, particularly given the clout of India’s economic growth. India is rising, and a state such as Britain needs higher trade with India, so they are willing to downplay elements from his past.”</p> <p>The Leicester MP <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/keithvaz\">Keith Vaz</a>, an enthusiastic cheerleader for the Modi visit, said it marked not only a “coming of age” for British Indians – “the community has organised the event, raised the money, booked the biggest venue in the country, without asking anyone’s permission” – but also an important shift in the power dynamic between the two countries.</p> <p>“It is now a relationship of equals, but more than that, you have Indian companies like Tata who are able to buy landmark British companies like <a href=\"http://www.jaguarlandrover.com/gl/en/about-us/our-history/\">Jaguar Land Rover</a> or <a href=\"http://www.tatasteeleurope.com/en/about-us/heritage\">Corus</a>, and are <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/20/tata-steel-expected-to-announce-1200-job-losses-in-uk\">also able to close them</a>. That was unthinkable 30-40 years ago. There’s no question the balance has tilted.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"0667ed8b062e967a250facacf7d0b04d1f929373\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0667ed8b062e967a250facacf7d0b04d1f929373/275_27_3384_2031/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Modi with Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Modi with Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg – the prime minister sees connecting 600,000 villages across India using fibre optic cable as part of his dream to expand the world’s largest democracy’s economy.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Bloomberg via Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>But for all the wild enthusiasm in sections of the Indian diaspora, to others his visit to the UK is less welcome. More than 40 MPs have <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/early-day-motions/edm-detail1/?session=2015-16&amp;edmnumber=257\">signed an early day motion</a> urging Cameron to ensure issues of human rights are discussed during Modi’s visit. In <a href=\"https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/asia-and-the-pacific/india/report-india/\">its annual report</a> this year, Amnesty International criticised Modi’s government, saying there had been a rise in communal violence and repeated instances of human rights abuses by armed groups, while arrests and detentions of campaigners and journalists had persisted. </p> <p>The novelist Arundhati Roy became the latest literary figure to <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/05/arundhati-roy-returns-award-protest-religious-intolerance-india-bollywood-modi-government-violence\">return an award</a> <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/why-i-am-returning-my-award/\">in protest</a> at growing religious violence in the country since the advent of the BJP government. And in a sign of deepening troubles back home, Modi’s party suffered a crushing defeat in state elections in the northern province of Bihar, a sign that <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/08/narendra-modis-party-concedes-defeat-in-bihar-election\">its divisive sectarian rhetoric </a>is proving less effective. </p> <p>“Nobody doubts that there has to be a relationship between the Indian government and the British government, but I think that this stage-managed, high profile acceptance of Mr Modi just shows the hypocrisy of this government’s stance on human rights across the globe,” said Suresh Grover, of <a href=\"http://www.tmg-uk.org/\">The Monitoring Group</a>, one of a number of campaign groups planning a demonstration outside Downing Street when Modi arrives on Thursday. On Sunday <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/modi-uk-visit-british-indians-protest-indian-prime-minister-projection-onto-parliament-1527815\">campaigners projected a huge sign reading “Modi Not Welcome”</a> on to the side of the Houses of Parliament.</p> <p>Both Jeremy Corbyn, the Labour leader, and John McDonnell, the shadow chancellor, were among the signatories to the EDM, as well as the SNP’s Alex Salmond, the Green MP Caroline Lucas and Peter Bottomley, the sole Conservative on the list. Corbyn is expected to raise the issues in person with Modi during his visit. Vaz said he believed Corbyn’s support for the EDM was “unwise” and that human rights was not “an appropriate point on this visit”.</p> <p>But to Gupta and tens of thousands of ordinary British Indians, Modi’s ambition to turn India into a true global superpower, as symbolised in his immense welcome party, is a source of immense pride. “Because India is no longer a very poor country, although there are a lot of poor people there, there has been a change in how we are viewed over here. No Indian prime minister has struck gold with the people who live here like he has.”</p> <h2>Protests expected against Modi visit</h2> <p><em>Harriet Sherwood</em></p> <p>Several thousand people are expected to attend a demonstration against the visit of the Indian prime minister, Narendra Modi, to the UK this week. Critics say Modi’s government is cracking down on religious freedom and the campaigning work of NGOs and civil society organisations.</p> <p>An alliance of Muslims, Sikhs, Christians and representatives of the Dalit caste are among those backing the protest, which is being coordinated by the Awaaz network. The action has also gathered support from women’s groups, human rights groups, academics and students, anti-racist organisations and artists. The protest will begin at noon on Thursday outside Downing Street and move to Parliament Square.</p> <p>“There’s no doubt that Modi represents a political current that’s very rightwing, but this [protest] is really about an attack on the constitutional values of secular and religious freedom in India,” said Suresh Grover, of Awaaz.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p> <p></p> <p>The group says Modi’s government “has created an authoritarian culture that is directly contrary to India’s democratic principles”. It cites attacks on minorities, including Muslims, Christians, LGBT groups, secularists, women, Dalit and numerous NGOs.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"75aa8d43e94de1cad0f4c823bd7427c90259843a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/75aa8d43e94de1cad0f4c823bd7427c90259843a/0_119_5520_3314/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A protest against the lynching in October of a Muslim farmer by Hindus upon hearing rumours that the family was eating beef.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A protest against the lynching in October of a Muslim farmer by Hindus upon hearing rumours that the family was eating beef.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Altaf Qadri/AP</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Among the NGOs that have faced restrictions on activity in India are Greenpeace and Amnesty International. Licences for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/law/2015/aug/26/ngos-face-restrictions-laws-human-rights-generation\">more than 13,000 organisations have been revoked</a> for alleged violations of a law on foreign funding.<br /></p> <p>Awaaz, which describes itself as a “UK-based secular network of individuals and organisations committed to monitoring and combating religious hatred in South Asia and in the UK”, claims that attacks against religious minorities in India have risen by 25% in the past year. The attacks have included <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/03/inside-bishari-indian-village-where-mob-killed-man-for-eating-beef\">the lynching of a Muslim man</a> in Bishara village who was believed by his Hindu neighbours to have eaten meat from a cow.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p> <p>Muslims make up 14.2% of India’s 1.2bn-plus citizens, Christians 2.3% and Sikhs 1.7%, <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.census2011.co.in/religion.php\">according to the 2011 census.</a> Hindus form the vast majority of the population.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p> <p>Awaaz is also urging people to boycott the “stage-managed” pro-Modi rally at Wembley stadium on Friday. “His fanatic followers treat him like a god rather than what he is – an authoritarian politician, deeply fond of expensive designer clothing, unable to answer unscripted questions, who remains silent about the grotesque fundamentalist violence that brought him to power and made him who he is,” <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://awaaz-uk.org/protest-narendra-modis-visit-to-the-uk/\">says the Awaaz website</a>. </p>","internalOctopusCode":"10970763","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403000","internalRevision":"1326","internalContentCode":"458349927","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Wembley stadium event to welcome Hindu nationalist leader but protests over human rights threaten to spoil the party","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Rock star reception lined up for visit of Indian prime minister Narendra Modi","byline":"Esther Addley","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T11:02:52Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b97b08708818aa7387b8c23608f5c58bdd51db04/304_300_2610_1566/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563ce3b0e4b09da63347fc25","newspaperPageNumber":"14","standfirst":"<p>Wembley stadium event to welcome Hindu nationalist leader but protests over human rights threaten to spoil the party</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-06T17:30:24Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-1