a>has rendered that strategy obsolete.</p> <p>It has also been hit by overcapacity among major brewers, with mass-market brands coming under pressure from more premium “craft” beers. Carlsberg acknowledged the so-called craft beer revolution this year by expanding its Crafted range of quality ales, lagers and stouts that it sells to pubs. </p> <p>These include third-party brands such as the Californian ale Lagunitas IPA, as well as some from its own stable such as the Backyard Brewery, part of its Falkenberg operation in Sweden.</p> <p>It plans to cut production volumes and focus on improving its image, which has suffered despite sponsoring the Premier League and England football team. </p> <p>Analyst Trevor Stirling, at Bernstein, said: ‘‘In order to stay in Tesco they were putting money into price promotions instead of investing. They need to put more money behind the brand.”</p> <p>Carlsberg UK’s difficulties led it to it ask suppliers to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/10/carlsberg-joins-hall-of-shame-for-delaying-supplier-payments\">wait an extra three months for payment</a>, a request branded “grossly unfair” this week by the Forum of Private Business. The company said on Tuesday it was starting a “formal review of its customer supply chain operations”.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/10/carlsberg-joins-hall-of-shame-for-delaying-supplier-payments\">Carlsberg  joins 'Hall of Shame' for delaying supplier payments</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Michiel Herkemij has been appointed interim chief executive to oversee the planned job cuts and strategic shift. “Unfortunately the proposed restructuring process may result in redundancies in some areas of the business and we will support the impacted employees through the consultation period,” he said. </p> <p>Union officials are due to meet with Carlsberg management next week to discuss the proposed cuts.</p> <p>Carlsberg’s third quarter loss was largely caused by a £732m cut in the value of its Russian and Chinese businesses, part of £948m in anticipated impairments by 2017.</p> <p>Drinkers in Russia have been switching to cheaper brands amid dismal economic conditions and a tumbling rouble, which has made foreign imports even more expensive. A turnaround plan in China also failed to bear fruit amid the twin challenges of a declining market and more intense competition.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971500","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405513","internalRevision":"525","internalContentCode":"458370600","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Global production cuts expected to threaten nearly 100 jobs at Danish firm’s Northampton brewery, Leeds office and 12 UK distribution depots","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Carlsberg to axe 2,000 staff as sales fall flat","byline":"Rob Davies","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T18:27:25Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/4d9ed56345c30f081778f564dc73b0c8a70569a2/0_1080_1610_968/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"56437309e4b04096fed8b4ed","newspaperPageNumber":"34","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T18:30:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Global production cuts expected to threaten nearly 100 jobs at Danish firm’s Northampton brewery, Leeds office and 12 UK distribution depots</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-11T16:55:37Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-11T23:15:04.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/11/carlsberg-axe-2000-staff-sales-fall-flat","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2015/nov/11/carlsberg-axe-2000-staff-sales-fall-flat","sectionName":"Business","elements":[{"id":"4d9ed56345c30f081778f564dc73b0c8a70569a2","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"imag