n-north-east-england-100000\">prices rose strongly</a> in 2014, surveyors were much less likely to report price rises. Looking ahead over the next three months, 5% more of those questioned in the capital said they expected prices to rise than to fall. </p> <p>Figures from mortgage lenders show there has been an increase in lending since the spring, while HM Revenue &amp; Customs has reported an increase in transactions. Rics said members in every region except London and the east Midlands had seen a pick-up in the number of sales agreed in October.</p> <p>Rics’s chief economist, Simon Rubinsohn, said: “It is hard to get away from the issue of supply when it comes to the current state of the housing market. </p> <p>“The legacy of the drop in new build, following the onset of the global financial crisis, is now really hitting home, with both the sales and letting markets continuing to show demand outstripping supply on a month-by-month basis.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/09/economics-housing-britain-political-policy-communities\">The economics of scale: how housing became Britain’s biggest political issue | Andy Beckett</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Rics members said they expected prices to rise by just less than 4.5% a year for the next five years, an increase that would add £42,000 to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2015/oct/28/average-london-home-500000-in-north-east-england-100000\">average cost of a home</a> in England and Wales. The cost of renting is expected to rise at a similar rate over the same period, as demand from tenants stays strong. Around the UK, demand for rented homes continues to outstrip supply, said Rics. </p> <p>“If the five-year projections from members regarding the outlook for both prices and rents is anything to go by, property is set to become even more unaffordable going forward, making the government’s focus on boosting the delivery of new homes absolutely critical,” said Rubinsohn. <br /></p> <p>Alan Williams, from the Colchester branch of estate agency Fenn Wright, said there was still a lot of demand in the market. “Any fall-throughs we have are reselling quickly, and often at higher figures,” he added.</p> <p>Another agent in East Anglia, Chris Philpot, of Lacy Scott and Knight in Stowmarket, said: “The market has now tailed off after a hectic summer, but strong prices are still being achieved. Instead of vendors dropping prices to sell during the last months of 2015, buyers are paying good prices to make a purchase before the winter.” </p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971547","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405409","internalRevision":"1088","internalContentCode":"458369507","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors says number of homes coming up for sale has fallen for nine months in a row","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Property shortages keep driving up prices, say experts","byline":"Hilary Osborne","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-12T00:01:02Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/8dd761fdec9d3dbf2df6d29ec57f8b24e86f18f8/0_0_3500_2101/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"56435d07e4b091de41c2c0b6","newspaperPageNumber":"36","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-15T00:01:02Z","standfirst":"<p>Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors says number of homes coming up for sale has fallen for nine months in a row</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-11T15:21:43Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-12T00:03:09.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/12/property-shortages-keep-driving-up-prices-say-experts","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/society/2015/nov/12/property-shortages-keep-driving-up-prices-say-experts",