ia-id=\"9f425ef8a8315a5ebf27ebe0ae491e46783cfdee\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9f425ef8a8315a5ebf27ebe0ae491e46783cfdee/0_193_5708_3425/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Welder in factory\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A welder works on machinery in a British factory. The latest data shows continuing improvement in the labour market, according to the ONS. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9f425ef8a8315a5ebf27ebe0ae491e46783cfdee/0_193_5708_3425/140.jpg","body":"<p>Pay growth for Britain’s workers appears to be slowing sharply, raising questions about the durability of the recent improvement in living standards.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171778_421089.pdf\">Official figures</a> published on Wednesday showed the labour market remained healthy in the three months to September, with the employment rate hitting a record high of 73.7%, and the unemployment rate sliding to 5.3%, its lowest level for more than seven years.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/08/ghosts-financial-crashes-past-haunt-consumer-christmas\">Ghosts of crashes past still haunt this consumer Christmas</a> </p> </aside>  <p>However, earnings growth has weakened. On a three-monthly basis, regular wages, excluding bonuses, grew at an annual rate of 2.5% in the three months to September, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/14/unemployment-wage-rises-figures-ons-george-osborne\">down from 2.8% in the three months to August</a>. Including bonuses, wage growth was unchanged, at 3%.</p> <p>Looking at the more volatile monthly data, the deterioration was more marked, with regular pay growth slipping to just 1.9%, the weakest since January.</p> <p>With <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/13/uk-inflations-dips-below-zero\">inflation at -0.1%</a>, driven by the continuing weakness in commodity prices, real wages are rising at a healthy rate; but take-home pay remains well below pre-crisis levels, and the slowdown raised concerns about what would happen once inflation starts to pick up again.</p> <p>Frances O’Grady, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, described the data as “especially worrying, given that the government is about to announce severe cuts, which will reduce demand across the economy, making pay growth harder to maintain”.</p> <p>Over the past year, almost three quarters of the jobs created have gone to non-UK nationals, predominantly from inside the EU, according to the Office for National Statistics, a fact that is likely to sharpen the debate about free movement as David Cameron seeks to renegotiate Britain’s relationship with Brussels. </p> <p>The number of UK nationals in jobs jumped by 122,000 in a year, to 28.09 million, the ONS said; while the number of non-UK nationals working in the UK increased by 326,000, to 3.22 million.</p> <p>The Bank of England’s <a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/agentssummary/2015/nov.pdf\">monthly report</a> from its local agents up and down the country, also published on Wednesday, offered separate evidence of weakness, saying that while pay pressure was building in some sectors, “hiring intentions had eased, alongside slower demand growth and an increasing focus on raising productivity”.</p> <p>Matthew Whittaker, chief economist at the Resolution Foundation thinktank, said improvements in productivity would be the key to generating wage rises in the coming months. “The good news is that signs of a return to productivity growth should generate more upward pay pressure. That will be particularly important once inflation starts to rise.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/nov/10/ten-things-you-should-know-about-the-gender-pay-gap\">Ten facts you might not know about the gender pay gap | Laura Bates</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The rapid improvement in the labour market has been one of the strongest features of Britain’s economic recovery in recent years. Nick Palmer, of the ONS, said: “These figures continue the recent strengthening trend in the labour market, with a new record high in the employment rate and the unemployment rate still at its lowest since spring 2008.”</p> <p>George Osborne, keen to cement his reputation for economic management amid the tax credits controversy, said the figures were “excellent news”. The chancellor added: “At 73.7% our employment rate has never been higher and we are moving towards the goal of full employment <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/mar/31/george-osborne-full-employment-britain-inflation\">that I set out a year ago</a>.”</p> <p></p> <p><br /></p> <p>However the weakening of pay growth is likely to undermine the argument of anti-inflation hawks on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/05/interest-rate-bank-of-england-leave-record-low-decision\">Bank of England’s monetary policy committee</a>, who have argued that interest rates should rise to prevent wage growth running out of control. </p> <p>John Philpott, of the Jobs Economist consultancy firm, said: “While we can continue to take comfort in the general health of the UK employment situation there is nothing in these latest data to support the kind of ‘overheating labour market’ narrative that might be used to suggest the Bank of England should start to raise interest rates sooner rather than later.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971442","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405069","internalRevision":"1250","internalContentCode":"458366811","publication":"The Guardian","t