l":"http://gu.com/p/4e547","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2030d3c714c8c0854acd70cd2bf07647c445ca00\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2030d3c714c8c0854acd70cd2bf07647c445ca00/0_38_640_384/500.jpg\" alt=\"Vacuum cleaner\" width=\"500\" height=\"300\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Dyson says that current tests don’t take into account drop in energy efficiency when vacuum cleaner bags are full. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Werner Dieterich/Westend61/Corbis</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/2030d3c714c8c0854acd70cd2bf07647c445ca00/0_38_640_384/140.jpg","body":"<p></p> <p></p> <p>Dyson is considering launching an appeal after its legal bid to change the EU energy labelling of vacuum cleaners – based on its claims that rival models were receiving misleadingly high ratings - was thrown out by a European court.</p> <p>The British technology giant, founded by billionaire engineer and entrepreneur Sir James Dyson, argued that machines were only tested when they were empty of dust which could “mislead consumers on the real environmental impact of the machine they are buying”. </p> <p>But on Wednesday the <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://curia.europa.eu/jcms/upload/docs/application/pdf/2015-11/cp150133en.pdf\">European Court of Justice (ECJ) said</a> it had dismissed Dyson’s action “in its entirety” because the company – best known for its bagless vacuum cleaner – had failed to demonstrate that there were more reliable, accurate and reproducible tests than the one endorsed by the European commission. It concluded that Dyson’s action for “annulment of the regulation on energy labelling of vacuum cleaners” had been unsuccessful.</p> <p>Dyson Ltd branded the decision “deplorable” and said that the ECJ had failed to act in the interests of consumers. </p> <p>The company <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/21/anger-as-eu-bans-most-powerful-vacuum-cleaners\">launched its suit against the European commission last year</a>, arguing that its new system of eco-label tests misled consumers about real-world energy performance and add to environmental damage. <br /></p> <p>The new EU energy label, introduced from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/21/anger-as-eu-bans-most-powerful-vacuum-cleaners\">1 September</a>, means manufacturers are not be able to make or import vacuum cleaners with a motor that exceeds 1,600 watts.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p> <p>The ECJ said in its ruling: “Dyson states that the regulation misleads consumers because the cleaning performance is tested only when the vacuum cleaner’s receptacle is empty and not during use. The court acknowledges that the suction performance and energy efficiency of a vacuum cleaner with a dust-loaded receptacle will be reduced due to dust accumulation.</p> <p>“It observes, however, that the [European] commission could not use tests conducted on the basis of a dust-loaded receptacle, as they are not reliable, accurate and reproducible, as required by the regulation.”</p> <p>The court also dismissed Dyson’s claim that current EU energy labelling laws “discriminate” in favour of bagged vacuum cleaners. <br /></p> <p>A spokesman for Dyson Ltd said the company was “reviewing its legal options, including the possibility of an appeal.”</p> <p>It said in a statement: “It is deplorable that the European Court of Justice endorses tests that don’t attempt to represent in-home use, and we believe this is causing consumers to be misled. The ECJ’s assertion that dust-loaded testing is not reliable defies belief; the dust loaded test method was devised by the IEC (International Electrotechnical Commission) and has been adopted by consumer test bodies and manufacturers worldwide.” </p> <p>In its highly critical statement, it went on: “By this judgment, the ECJ has given its support to unrepresentative tests devised by the commission with a small group of European manufacturers which in our view disregards the interests of consumers in Europe... The judgment is all the more surprising in view of the revelations about car testing in the <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/sep/25/vw-emissions-scandal-seven-days\">VW scandal</a> where the tests do not reflect real life usage.”</p> <p>Ukip MEP Margot Parker, the party’s small business spokeswoman, said: “It is sad to see the European Court of Justice strike down a fair and reasonable complaint with such ease. Evidently the form of testing used does not allow for an equal evaluation of different types of vacuums. Unfortunately for Sir James Dyson, he has found himself on the end of yet more anti-competitive, bureaucratic and ill-conceived European regulation.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971736","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405086","internalRevision":"665","internalContentCode":"458367021","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Company says ruling is against consumer interests after court dismisses Dyson’s argument that tests discriminate in favour of bagged vacuum cleaners and lead to misleadingly high ratings","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Dyson considers appealing court rule against changing EU energy labelling laws","byline":"Rebecca Smithers","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T10:48:41Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2030d3c714c8c0854acd70cd2bf07647c445ca00/0_38_640_384/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"5643153de4b08b339848c3d4","newspaperPageNumber":"34","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T10:45:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Company says ruling is against consumer interests after court dismisses Dyson’s argument that tests discriminate in favour of bagged vacuum cleaners and lead to misleadingly high ratings</p>",