e35ed5fbf675ceb35a7379e0ddca1c0db863c/63_49_1989_1194/140.jpg","body":"<p>Lidl is to invest £1.5bn over the next three years as it steps up its store expansion with new-look outlets that include self-checkouts – and customer toilets.</p> <p>The German discounter said it was aiming to open 40-50 stores a year in the UK, up from the 30-40 previously planned and the 20 opened in 2014.</p> <p>The fast-growing company, which has helped revolutionise British shopping habits, will also refurbish up to 150 existing sites to its “store of the future” concept over the next three to four years.</p> <p>Lidl will open the first £2m store of the future in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Thursday. The 1,400 sq metres building is one of the first Lidl stores in the UK with customer toilets, baby changing facilities and self-checkouts.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"b6f0dcf5ab80baf63f2e385c70a7c2c37a5b905a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/b6f0dcf5ab80baf63f2e385c70a7c2c37a5b905a/0_138_2121_1276/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Lidl is revamping its wine departments.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"602\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Lidl is revamping its wine departments.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Lidl</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>These features, common in mainstream supermarkets, mark a move upmarket for the discounter chain. The new stores will also feature longer tills so customers can pack at the checkout, wider aisles and glass frontages to make them lighter.</p> <p>Bryan Roberts, at retail the analysis firm Kantar, said the Rushden store combined features that Lidl had tested in a handful of other stores. The introduction of bakeries, deluxe food ranges and revamped wine departments were designed to appeal to middle-class shoppers, he said.</p> <p>“Lidl is definitely chasing a more upmarket clientele as well as its traditional shopper base,” Roberts said. “The worry is that it is adding costs and complexity into a model where the heritage has always been being brutally efficient with a very narrow [range of products]. Arguably, the distinction between a supermarket and a discounter is ebbing away.”</p> <p>Ingo Fischer, Lidl UK’s board director of property and expansion, said the new stores would improve efficiency and help streamline the group’s processes. “This forms a key part of our business model, which enables us to keep prices low and the quality of our products high,” he said.</p> <p>As well as wider aisles, the stores will include better facilities such as improved staff rooms andenergy efficient LED lighting. Lidl plans to recycle heat from its refrigerators to warm the store so its operations are cheaper and greener than traditional outlets.<br tabindex=\"-1\" /></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971247","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405443","internalRevision":"1183","internalContentCode":"458369953","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Budget supermarket attempts to woo wealthier clientele with revamped wine cellar and deluxe food ranges in energy efficient ‘store of the future’","allowUgc":"false","headline":"A Lidl bigger: £1.5bn store expansion to include self-checkouts and toilets","byline":"Sarah Butler","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T18:07:55Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b7ce35ed5fbf675ceb35a7379e0ddca1c0db863c/63_49_1989_1194/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"564364c9e4b099e7a86ec5f6","newspaperPageNumber":"37","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T18:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Budget supermarket attempts to woo wealthier clientele with revamped wine cellar and deluxe food ranges in energy efficient ‘store of the future’</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-11T15:54:49Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-12T10:04:50.522Z","