olitan Police","mediaId":"7953a9123875c284fb3d859c15cc3dbbd40d6e67","displayCredit":"true","credit":"Photograph: Metropolitan Police","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/7953a9123875c284fb3d859c15cc3dbbd40d6e67/0_0_5163_3100/master/5163.jpg","width":"5163","height":"3100","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/uknews","webTitle":"UK news","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"uk-news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/uknews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/uknews","sectionName":"UK news"}]},{"id":"tv-and-radio/2015/nov/11/breaking-bad-smithsonian-museum-props-bryan-cranston-aaron-paul","type":"article","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","webTitle":"Breaking Bad cast visits Smithsonian museum as show's props join collection","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T14:08:05Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1249","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e5vj","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa/0_67_3000_1800/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Breaking Bad Smithsonian\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Breaking Bad actors Aaron Paul and Bryan Cranston pose with their Tyvek suits during a donation ceremony of artifacts from the show at the Smithsonian.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Kris Connor/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa/0_67_3000_1800/140.jpg","body":"<p>Its collection includes George Washington’s trunk, the top hat worn by Abraham Lincoln on the night of his assassination, and the flag that inspired Francis Scott Key to write <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/aug/11/malcolm-gladwell-star-spangled-banner-america-200th-anniversary\">the Star-Spangled Banner</a>.</p> <p>And now, Walter White’s crystal meth.</p> <p>The Smithsonian’s <a href=\"http://americanhistory.si.edu/\">National Museum of American History</a> in Washington hosted cast and crew of the TV drama <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/breaking-bad\">Breaking Bad</a> on Tuesday, taking into custody more than 10 of its props “to recognise the show’s influence on American culture”.</p> <p>The series made a low-key start in 2008 but came to join the likes of The Sopranos, The Wire, Mad Men and House of Cards in the binge-viewing, box set pantheon, scooping numerous awards over five seasons. It followed the moral descent of White, played by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/bryan-cranston\">Bryan Cranston</a>, a chemistry teacher who, after being diagnosed with terminal cancer, makes and deals in crystal methamphetamine to support his family.</p> <p>“Artifacts” donated to the museum include two yellow Tyvek suits and gas masks used by White and his former-student-turned-business partner Jesse Pinkman (Aaron Paul) while cooking in their lab, and a small plastic bag of the “Blue Sky” meth they manufactured. There is also an ID card belonging to White’s brother-in-law Hank Schrader, a drugs law enforcement agent, and a paper cup from Los Pollos Hermanos, a fast food restaurant and front for money laundering in Albuquerque, New Mexico, where the tale is set.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"22bb7bbab3b01b2a8c092b4958f84357f4b1c023\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/22bb7bbab3b01b2a8c092b4958f84357f4b1c023/0_190_3296_1982/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Bryan Cranston in the Heisenberg hat worn by his character, Walter White.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Bryan Cranston in the Heisenberg hat worn by his character, Walter White.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Patsy Lynch/REX Shutterstock</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>At Tuesday’s informal and jocular handover ceremony, Cranston walked over to a table displaying the props and put on the black <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NfdjBz8E_dw\">“Heisenberg hat” </a>– an alias borrowed from Werner Heisenberg, the scientist who formulated the uncertainty principle – he wore for much of the series.</p> <p>Amid laughter, wistful exclamations and rapid clicking of cameras, Cranston told the audience: “I wanted to see if it still fit. Thank you, everybody. Boy, it feels strange putting that back on.”</p> <p>He told fellow cast members he misses them but added: “I don’t miss the show, though. I’m asked often, do you miss playing this character, and the truth is, after really some reflection, that I don’t because Vince [<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/aug/18/breaking-bad-vince-gilligan-walter-white\">Gilligan, series creator</a>] and the writers created and crafted such a perfectly designed beginning, middle and end to this journey. People said incredulously, why wouldn’t you want to continue?</p> <p>“I said, it feels like we had a beautiful meal. We had an aperitif, a nice salad, a beautiful entree, a vegetable side, we had a great dessert and we had a coffee with it and you’re just satiated, and then someone says here’s more dessert. If you dived into that then it almost ruins the experience you had. I don’t know if my personage could take another dessert after the sweet ride that Breaking Bad was.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"27e2410cf65646b59ccfffd4563ce274fe9d9f40\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/27e2410cf65646b59ccfffd4563ce274fe9d9f40/0_177_2992_1798/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Dean Norris, who played Hank Schrader, poses near some of the props.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Dean Norris, who played Hank Schrader, poses near some of the props.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Patsy Lynch/REX Shutterstock</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Later Cranston, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jun/09/bryan-cranston-scoops-tony-award-for-best-actor-in-broadway-debut\">who last year won a Tony award</a> for his Broadway debut playing president Lyndon B Johnson, toured a gallery devoted to American presidents and first ladies and was informed that Johnson used to drop in at the museum from the White House. The actor’s recent work also includes <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/sep/13/trumbo-review-bryan-cranston-toronto-tiff\">Trumbo</a>, a biopic in which he plays blacklisted Hollywood screenwriter Dalton Trumbo.</p> <p>But it will be hard to repeat the runaway success of Breaking Bad which, having initially struggled to get studio backing, won awards including 16 Primetime Emmys and two Golden Globes. “I think the thing that really resonated was that Breaking Bad was a story of an average man who made decisions both good and bad, mostly bad,” Cranston told the Guardian. “People related to the sense of going from paycheque to paycheque and having desperate needs at home and the plight of teachers, the burnout sensation facing apathetic students every day. A man lost and depressed – it’s a very relatable thing – and how he makes a decision that turns out to be the worst in his life.</p> <p>“But if you asked Walter White if you regret making those decisions, I think he would be hard pressed to change his mind after two years of an exciting life or maybe three years of withering away and shrinking as a person. I think he didn’t want that, he wanted to go out more on his terms if that was possible, and I think that’s very relatable as well to people.”</p> <p>Cranston, 59, said he hoped the series would open the way for less conventional forms of narrative in the future. “I think it’s wide open. I think Breaking Bad showed the world that storytelling can be small or large, you can slow the pace down, people won’t just click off as the prevailing thought was. ‘If you’re not fast paced, they’re going to leave you,’ and they didn’t leave you. We were able to slow it down and that made the drama even more intense at times.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"055a38a63eba9b727f5c3b8458572a23caf269ba\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/055a38a63eba9b727f5c3b8458572a23caf269ba/0_0_3500_2304/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Yellow Tyvek suits are taken away after the memorabilia donation.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"658\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Yellow Tyvek suits are taken away after the memorabilia donation.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Gary Cameron/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Gilligan, whose writing credits include The X-Files, used to visit the Smithsonian’s National Air and Space Museum as a boy and admitted on Tuesday he felt he was dreaming. </p> <p>“I honestly thought Breaking Bad would never really get made. If you had told me in 2005 that props from our show would eventually find their way into the Smithsonian’s National Museum of American History, this same hallowed institution which houses the Star-Spangled Banner, Edison’s first lightbulb, Dorothy’s ruby slippers, Abraham Lincoln’s pocket watch, I would have thought you were using too much meth.”</p> <p>Currently overseeing the Breaking Bad spin-off <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/better-call-saul\">Better Call Saul</a>, which two weeks ago hosted fan Warren Buffett on set, Gilligan made clear that White has run his course but hinted that other characters from the fictional universe could return. “I almost feel like it would be bad form or bad karma to go back to that well, but having said that I don’t know, check with me in a few years. I don’t think there’s any more story to tell about Walter White necessarily, but maybe, who knows, some other characters who survive the series may have further that we might decide later that we wish to tell. But right now I really do feel like Brian, I feel like I’m satiated and it was time to push back from the dinner table, as it were.”</p> <p>The loss of both Breaking Bad and Mad Men <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/apr/01/mad-mens-final-series-the-bittersweet-joy-of-saying-goodbye\">left some viewers bereft</a>. But Gilligan rejected the notion that the golden age of US television drama has passed.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1f4c974c98d693c412bde34ddd86f25437b5f7ec\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1f4c974c98d693c412bde34ddd86f25437b5f7ec/0_75_3500_2103/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The Heisenberg Hat is displayed.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Heisenberg Hat is displayed.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Gary Cameron/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“I think there are many more great shows to come and I will be very jealous when even more great ones come along and surpass ours but I think it’s all to the good,” he said. “I grew up watching three or four channels and now we live in a world of hundreds of channels and there needs to be content for all those channels. It’s this amazing democratising technology that allows in theory for a television show for everybody.”</p> <p>The National Museum of American History’s best known entertainment exhibit is probably <a href=\"http://www.artlyst.com/articles/ruby-slippers-go-on-view-at-londons-va-museum\">a pair of ruby slippers</a> worn by Judy Garland in The Wizard of Oz. Its growing television collection includes objects from Mad Men, The Wonder Years, Seinfeld and All in the Family. But these, along with the Breaking Bad items, are not likely to go on display until a culture gallery opens in 2018.</p> <p>Dwight Bowers, the museum’s curator, told the audience: “It gives me great pause to think I’m the man who brought crystal meth to the museum.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10970590","productionOffice":"US","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2404990","internalRevision":"292","internalContentCode":"458366253","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Walter White’s crystal meth and Heisenberg hat join the likes of Edison’s first lightbulb in Washington as Bryan Cranston and Vince Gilligan visit the museum","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Breaking Bad cast visits Smithsonian museum as show's props join collection","byline":"David Smith in Washington","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T14:08:05Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa/0_67_3000_1800/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"5642c4c0e4b0ddf11c1fbf09","newspaperPageNumber":"3","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T14:15:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Walter White’s crystal meth and Heisenberg hat join the likes of Edison’s first lightbulb in Washington as Bryan Cranston and Vince Gilligan visit the museum</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-11T04:32:00Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-12T11:05:12.703Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/nov/11/breaking-bad-smithsonian-museum-props-bryan-cranston-aaron-paul","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2015/nov/11/breaking-bad-smithsonian-museum-props-bryan-cranston-aaron-paul","sectionName":"Television & radio","elements":[{"id":"86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa/0_67_3000_1800/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"2015 Kris Connor","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/86d9219b85da653824e1ff7cb4d2ccbecd3f39aa","suppliersRef