r-and-wide","type":"article","sectionId":"society","webTitle":"Crisis of funding in the NHS will be felt far and wide | Letters","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T19:44:38Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1707","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e5yd","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"62d83a499f5b2beeb4285023ebe48b62e7847565\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447264999646/A-nurse-with-a-patient-005.jpg\" alt=\"A nurse with a patient\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">'We are all potential patients, rich and poor alike, and to starve the NHS will ultimately have a negative impact on the health of the population as a whole,' writes Dr Keith Paver. Photograph: Christopher Furlong/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447264993236/A-nurse-with-a-patient-001.jpg","body":"<p>What a relief to read the article by Christopher Smallwood speaking truth to power (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/08/nhs-chairman-funding-crisis-collapse\" title=\"\">NHS finances are in a critical condition</a>, 9 November). He sets out the financial facts behind the current problems facing many hospitals in the NHS, and describes the inevitable consequences to clinical services and their patients if the government continues with its current approach. I come at this debate from two perspectives: as a retired hospital CEO and as a patient of St George’s Hospital over the last year.</p> <p>I know that the NHS has faced financial challenges on previous occasions and has for many years found a series of efficiency savings. However, as Smallwood points out, efficiency savings are not a bottomless pit. High quality and safe patient services (apparently a government objective), which I have personally experienced at St George’s, cannot be delivered with inadequate funding. Nor can they be delivered well when the financial bottom line becomes organisationally the over-riding priority.</p> <p>Many reports on “inadequate” services in the NHS, including those from the Care Quality Commission, focus on a lack of leadership, rather than lack of funding, as the root cause of the problems encountered. Smallwood is spelling out to the government that they need a major rethink of the NHS funding settlement. Let’s hope they listen and act.<br /><strong>Mary Wells</strong><br /><em>London</em></p> <p>• As a fellow chair of an NHS foundation trust in Cumbria I fully support all the points made by Christopher Smallwood, chair of St George’s Trust. I have been making similar points for the last three months (in a personal capacity) with particular emphasis on two things:</p> <p>1) We were never consulted about the viability of making £22bn efficiency/productivity savings by 2020. Had we been then I for one would have argued that there is no known evidence from any sector – private, public or third, and I have worked in all three – of this level of savings being achieved by these means. In the private sector, in my experience, if a product or service cannot pay its way then the company will generally withdraw from providing it. This leads to the second point:</p> <p>2) If insufficient money is to be made available for the ever increasing demands made on the NHS, as so clearly identified by Smallwood, then there needs to be a national political debate about what that actually means for the NHS. Are we expected to reduce staffing (which, of course, is the biggest single element of expenditure) thereby compromising quality of service delivery? Or are we expected to make local decisions about which services we can no longer afford to deliver? While this national debate is not taking place, and the consequences of funding decisions are being ignored, individual trusts are struggling, but increasingly failing, to meet the demands of their regulators to achieve savings that everyone knows are impossible. Soon individual trusts may well feel unable to resist suspending some services as no longer affordable – and we can all imagine the local outcry that would generate.<br /><strong>Mike Taylor</strong><br /><em>Clifton, Cumbria</em></p> <p>• Speaking out about the NHS financial situation is welcome but it does not tell the whole story, which is not just about the money. The stress on clinical staff is huge; shortages of key members of the team, high levels of demand and proposed contract changes are driving many to question their vocation and even to take strike action. Workforce planning failures are coming home to roost in hospitals, mental health and primary care. This is not just a financial crisis – the survival of the NHS as we know it is at stake.</p> <p>My trust is fast running out of cash and is reliant on forward payments from our commissioners. We are also running out of the precious commodity of staff in key specialities. Christopher Smallwood’s call for us to speak truth to power may be too late.<br /><strong>Dr Mike Williams</strong><br /><em>Non-executive director, Plymouth Hospitals NHS Trust</em></p> <p>• I read Christopher Smallwood’s piece with interest. I too have been a chairman of a big NHS hospital trust, for some 12 years, and I understand the pressures his trust is facing as well as anyone. There is an easy solution: throw more money at it. But at best, that can only be a part of the answer. If it is the whole answer, we will continue to pour public money into the health service at an unsustainable rate and – worse than that – will continue to treat many patients in the wrong place: the acute hospital.</p> <p>The right answer is more difficult: it is a combination of reducing clinical and operating variation in our hospitals, thereby improving quality and reducing waste; joining up care across all settings, particularly for those people who have long-term chronic conditions, who would be better treated out of hospital; and taking prevention seriously, especially the growing scourge of obesity.</p> <p>The government has committed extra spending of at least £10bn a year by 2020-21. It can do this because the economy is growing and the deficit is falling. It is backing the NHS’s own five-year plan. It is the right plan and as minister for NHS productivity I am proud to do so too.<br /><strong>David Prior</strong><br /><em>Parliamentary under-secretary of state for health </em></p> <p>• I have recently completed six years as a public governor of one of the largest NHS foundation trusts in the country, the last two as lead governor. I am daily filled with admiration at the heroics performed by all the staff of the trust, from chairman, chief executive and managers, down to the lowest paid ancillary, to provide the highest quality of medical care possible. Yet they do this with one hand tied behind their backs, and to make any one part of the whole perform at 100% efficiency means moving resources from somewhere else. The budget has been cut to the bone and capital projects postponed, even those that are vital to cope with ever increasing demand. We are all potential patients, rich and poor alike, and to starve the NHS in the way that this government is doing will ultimately have a negative impact on the health of the population as a whole.<br /><strong>Dr Keith Paver</strong><br /><em>Manchester</em></p> <p>• The Guardian has followed in the footsteps of the Financial Times which a few weeks ago stated that the government would be funding the NHS to the tune of £8bn per year during this parliament. Simon Stevens, head of the NHS, is quoted in different Guardian articles as stating that the funding during this parliament will be £8bn per year and £8bn in total.</p> <p>My understanding of Stevens’ Forward View document, published earlier this year, is that £30bn is the minimum needed to see the NHS through. £8bn per year would be just fine but is unfortunately a fanciful figure.</p> <p>Christopher Smallwood’s account of NHS finances is a concise and erudite account of the crisis in the NHS, and I hope that more staff, patients and board members will express their dismay about government policy which is wrecking the NHS.</p> <p>As a governor in a large NHS trust, I hope that other governors will campaign against the current funding arrangements in the run-up to the autumn statement. Most of us are elected and have a mandate to ensure that patient care is safe and of high quality.<br /><strong>Dr Veronica Beechey</strong><br /><em>London</em></p> <p>• What I could not find in Christopher Smallwood’s article is any reference to the “efficiency savings” that have been imposed on the NHS, which I assume is a euphemism for cuts, or to Mr Cameron’s pre-election promise to ringfence NHS budgets. This whole scenario reminds me of the run up to the privatisation of British Rail which at the time was being starved of public funding and accused of being inefficient. Private enterprise took over, wangled an even bigger subsidy out of the government and paid shareholders out of the proceeds.</p> <p>The next stage therefore as far as health is concerned, is for the government to declare that people should take out health insurance (a profitable business), private companies will run our hospitals (for profit) and GPs will charge for their services. The government then washes its hands of taking any responsibility for public health, and we adopt the American system which is the most expensive health provision in the world which makes a handsome profit for those businesses involved, and neglects to cater for the poorer members of our society. What a great reduction in the welfare budget!</p> <p>Already I notice an increase in TV adverts offering an opportunity to jump the NHS queues if you take out health insurance. Surely none of these companies are Tory party donors.<br /><strong>David Selby</strong><br /><em>South Wonston, Hampshire</em></p> <p>• Thank goodness that a senior experienced manager has at last spoken out about the funding crisis in the NHS. It is not surprising that hospitals are running a deficit as the tariff has been cut and they are not fully reimbursed for emergency work over target, a situation over which they have no control, despite which they are fined for not meeting targets. Staff cuts in order to balance the budget lead to demoralised staff which in turn increases sickness absence and increases use of more expensive agency staff. Mr Smallwood suggests that ministers are in denial but there is an alternative explanation, which is that this government is deliberately underfunding the NHS to drive it into failure. Over the last three financial years the NHS has retuned £7.5bn to the Treasury, £3.2bn in the last year which if used correctly by the NHS to pay hospitals for the work they have done would have prevented so may of them going into deficit. For years managers and clinicians have worked miracles to provide a good service despite cuts (often misleadingly called “efficiency savings”) and it is time that senior NHS staff stood up to the bullying tactics of the present secretary of sate for health and demanded that no more money is returned to the Treasury and that the money returned this year is reclaimed and is used for its proper purpose.<br /><strong>Wendy Savage</strong><br /><em>President, Keep Our NHS Public</em></p> <p><strong><em>• Join the debate – email </em></strong><a href=\"mailto:guardian.letters@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong><em>guardian.letters@theguardian.com</em></strong></a></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10969817","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405551","internalRevision":"15","internalContentCode":"458371018","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"<strong>Letters:</strong> We are