s, which is a problem as women go through menopause and get older, and lessens the risk of fractures.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/10/leading-hrt-experts-not-consulted-over-nhs-menopause-guidance\">Leading HRT experts not consulted over NHS menopause guidance</a> </p> </aside>  <h2>How many women have taken HRT?</h2> <p>More than 100 million women worldwide.</p> <h2>In the UK?</h2> <p>Two million women were thought to be on it before studies revealed cancer risks. The numbers then halved.</p> <h2>What are the risks?</h2> <p>HRT is responsible for about five breast cancers per 1,000 women taking it for five years, studies have shown. The risk is low for women taking oestrogen only. When women stop taking the drugs, their risk returns to normal over about five years. HRT is also linked to one case of ovarian cancer per 1,000 women taking it for five years from the age of 50. There is also a very small increased risk of stroke.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971166","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2404728","internalRevision":"1117","internalContentCode":"458364108","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"What is it and how does it affect women? ","allowUgc":"false","headline":"A guide to the menopause","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-12T00:01:02Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/3f3d2f062147e4e635054dd865fd54d73ea07775/0_156_5200_3122/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"56421a5de4b00d947b614d3f","newspaperPageNumber":"4","standfirst":"<p>What is it and how does it affect women? </p>","creationDate":"2015-11-10T16:25:01Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-12T10:45:04.736Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/nov/12/a-