layCredit":"true","photographer":"Ch'ien Lee","credit":"Photograph: Ch'ien Lee/Corbis","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/1000.jpg","width":"1000","height":"600"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/500.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","suppliersReference":"67173795","altText":"Earless Monitor Lizard (Lanthanotus borneensis), Malaysia","source":"Corbis","mediaId":"d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Ch'ien Lee","credit":"Photograph: Ch'ien Lee/Corbis","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/500.jpg","width":"500","height":"300"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/140.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","suppliersReference":"67173795","altText":"Earless Monitor Lizard (Lanthanotus borneensis), Malaysia","source":"Corbis","mediaId":"d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Ch'ien Lee","credit":"Photograph: Ch'ien Lee/Corbis","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/6000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","suppliersReference":"67173795","altText":"Earless Monitor Lizard (Lanthanotus borneensis), Malaysia","source":"Corbis","mediaId":"d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Ch'ien Lee","credit":"Photograph: Ch'ien Lee/Corbis","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/6000.jpg","width":"6000","height":"3600"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/master/6000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","suppliersReference":"67173795","altText":"Earless Monitor Lizard (Lanthanotus borneensis), Malaysia","source":"Corbis","mediaId":"d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Ch'ien Lee","credit":"Photograph: Ch'ien Lee/Corbis","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d0e1f89f1abf02fa541340d2f0ae85fcc8025a78/0_342_6000_3600/master/6000.jpg","width":"6000","height":"3600","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/international","webTitle":"International","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/international","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/international","sectionName":"From the Guardian"}]},{"id":"world/2015/nov/11/narendra-modi-support-india-world-tour-uk","type":"article","sectionId":"world","webTitle":"Narendra Modi retains core support at home as world tour reaches UK","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T11:13:41Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1090","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2zk","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ca3026df012f5d0932990f4abd4a1078bda3c134\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/ca3026df012f5d0932990f4abd4a1078bda3c134/555_794_2535_1522/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Narendra Modi addresses a rally in Srinagar\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Narendra Modi addresses a rally in Srinagar, Indian Kashmir.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Farooq Khan/EPA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/ca3026df012f5d0932990f4abd4a1078bda3c134/555_794_2535_1522/140.jpg","body":"<p>Few people seek out Kalkaji, a scruffy, crowded neighbourhood on the smoggy, congested southern fringes of Delhi. This is a part of India that rarely appears on the itinerary of visiting dignitaries, in travel documentaries, or in gentle films featuring quirky run-down hotels, railways and monsoon rains.</p> <p>Yet one man who has paid significant attention to places like Kalkaji is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/narendra-modi\">Narendra Modi</a>, India’s prime minister. Without support from the inhabitants of such nondescript neighbourhoods, the 65-year-old would not have been able to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/16/narenda-modi-bjp-sweep-power-indian-elections\">win power in a landslide election result in May 2014</a>, crushing the centre-left Congress party.</p> <p>Modi arrives in London on Wednesday on the latest leg of what is turning into an 18-month world tour interspersed with frantic bursts of policymaking and campaigning in his homeland. The son of a tea seller from the western state of Gujarat will address parliament, meet David Cameron, talk with business leaders and have lunch with the Queen. </p> <p>He will also address a rally in Wembley stadium on Friday attended by supporters from among Britain’s <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171776_290558.pdf\">1.5 million-strong</a> Indian-origin community. If it follows previous precedent on both coasts of the US, the rally will be a stunning celebration of Indian identity and influence. There will be a Bollywood-influenced mix of dance, displays and speeches, rounded off with fireworks. Modi’s speech will be a familiar masala of nationalism, his own brand of economics and appeals to his audience’s cultural roots.</p> <p>With the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/cop-21-un-climate-change-conference-paris\">Paris climate change conference</a> opening within weeks, India’s “traditional” attachment to sustainable development may get a mention, as will the desire of Modi, an ascetic yoga devotee, to clean up the sacred but heavily polluted river Ganges. In New York he sought diaspora donations for the project.</p> <p>It is likely he will also talk of India’s diversity. “It will be about all the wonderful things he will do for India … and there will be a little bit about pluralism perhaps,” said Shekhar Gupta, an Indian journalist and analyst.</p> <p> This is more controversial ground. In recent months India’s image overseas has been battered by a series of incidents of sectarian violence. One of the worst was <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/03/inside-bishari-indian-village-where-mob-killed-man-for-eating-beef\">the lynching of a Muslim man</a> who was suspected of eating beef by a Hindu mob in a village on the outskirts of Delhi. Cows are sacred to Hindus and killing or selling their meat is illegal in most parts of India.</p> <p>Some criticise Modi, a Hindu nationalist, for failing to condemn such attacks clearly and quickly. Among critics are writers, intellectuals and film-makers who have launched a series of protests against what they say is a “climate of intolerance”.</p> <p>Last week Arundhati Roy, the prize-winning author and activist, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/05/arundhati-roy-returns-award-protest-religious-intolerance-india-bollywood-modi-government-violence\">added her voice</a>, saying minorities in India were “being forced to live in terror, unsure of when and from where the assault will come.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/06/returning-award-ashamed-india-arundhati-roy\">I am returning my award because I’m ashamed of what’s happening in India | Arundhati Roy</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Officials from the ruling <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/16/narenda-modi-bjp-sweep-power-indian-elections\">Bharatiya Janata party (BJP)</a> have dismissed the protests as politically motivated and manufactured. But whether such sentiments are as divorced from mainstream popular opinion as they believe is unclear. </p> <p>An outsider who started his career with India’s biggest rightwing Hindu revivalist organisation, Modi promised his compatriots a new, more prosperous, meritocratic and muscular India that neighbours would fear and respect, all without allowing western influence on conservative cultural and social values. It was a powerful vision that resonated with the newly expanded urban middle classes in Kalkaji and a multitude of scruffy suburbs like it. </p> <p>Modi’s own backstory – the poor man made good – also struck a chord. “There may have been an assumption that he was strong on these Hindu values because of his background, but what was really refreshing to voters was the emphasis on the economy, the opportunities for youth and business-friendly government,” said Samir Saran, of the Observer Research Foundation, a Delhi thinktank.</p> <p>Though India’s GDP growth rates are among the highest in the world, flagship tax reform legislation is stuck in parliament, investment in infrastructure remains as inadequate as ever, the promised economic take-off has been elusive and high-profile initiatives enjoining the population to sweep up the rubbish that fouls cities and fields alike have made little difference.</p> <p>If overseas investment analysts are worried, most people in Kalkaji are not. “Change is happening very slowly [here] because it is a big country. It takes time,” said Vijay Kumar, 57, a property dealer in the neighbourhood. “Modi’s performance is excellent. He’s a hardworking PM. Have you ever heard about him taking leave from work? He’s always working for India’s future.”</p> <p>Others were less impressed. “I expected him to keep a check on inflation. This affects the middle class the most, yet he has done nothing ,” said Poonam Sharma, who works in a local import-export company.</p> <p>Opinion in Kalkaji appeared divided on the issue of sectarian violence. “Yes. It has hurt his image. People think that he is working for Hindus only, but that’s not the case, he will help Muslims, too,” said Deepak Sharma, 25, an ATM service engineer.</p> <p> Kumar, the property dealer, blamed Modi’s subordinates for “making irresponsible statements and getting him into trouble”. </p> <p>Kalkaji is a predominantly Hindu neighbourhood. In Nizamuddin, a largely Muslim community nearer the centre of Delhi, views of Modi were overwhelmingly negative.</p> <p>Results in an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/08/narendra-modis-party-concedes-defeat-in-bihar-election\">election in the populous and poor eastern state of Bihar</a>, released on Sunday, revealed the potential impact of sectarian tension on Modi’s drive to reform India. During the bitter campaign, election authorities criticised the BJP for advertisements “of an offending nature” and banned several party posters they said could incite hatred.</p> <p>The party lost the election, despite Modi personally addressing 30 rallies. The defeat was the BJP’s <a href=\"http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/9HTFGjs8NXpc9A0kQtXPyN/Bihar-election-results-The-buck-stops-with-the-ModiShah-du.html\">most significant domestic setback</a> since taking power. </p> <p>“Modi needs to reflect on whether his mandate was for better governance and economic opportunism – that he still needs to deliver – or for a kind of communal agenda … Hindus are not used to this kind of aggressive form of propagation and find it distasteful,” said Saran, the analyst.</p> <p>Modi is still the most popular politician in the country and, as is likely to be shown by the welcome in Wembley, among the Indian diaspora. Few have much confidence in Rahul Gandhi, the lacklustre scion of India’s premier political family, who fronts the Congress. </p> <p>However, expectations for Modi remain high. “Yes, he’s the best leader in India. But let’s see what he does going forward,” said Prem Prakash, 35, an employee in an export company in Delhi.</p> <p><em>Additional reporting by Nikhil Cariappa</em></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10966269","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403452","internalRevision":"1182","internalContentCode":"458353659","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Indian PM has faced criticism over sectarian violence but he is still the most popular politician in the country and among the diaspora","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Narendra Modi retains core support at home as world tour reaches UK","byline":"Jason Burke","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T11:13:41Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/ca3026df012f5d0932990f4abd4a1078bda3c134/555_794_2535_1522/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563f8408e4b05e53c04d4e64","newspaperPageNumber":"14","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T11:13:41Z","standfirst":"<p>Indian PM has faced criticism over sectarian violence but he is still the most popular politician in the country and among the diaspora</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-08T17:19:04Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-11T22:01:04.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/11/narendra-modi-support-india-world-tour-uk","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/2015/nov/11/narendra-modi-support-india-world-tour-uk","sectionName":"World news","elements":[{"id":"ca3026df012f5d0932990f