_2954/140.jpg","body":"<p>The government will “cut off its nose to spite its face” if it slashes science spending and cuts investment grants in the comprehensive spending review this month, according to Chuka Umunna, the former Labour business spokesman.</p> <p>Speaking to manufacturing bosses in the Midlands on Wednesday, Umunna said Britain’s recovery would suffer a setback if the chancellor sought to make savings from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) and the grants that support productivity improvements and growth.</p> <p>Umunna, Labour MP for Streatham, said the BIS should be the engine room of the economy, supporting investment in infrastructure and innovative manufacturing processes needed to compete in the global economy.</p> <p>“I accept the need to reduce the debt and deficit – it is a waste to be spending over £30bn this year servicing our debts instead of investing it in people. But doing so by raiding growth-inducing budgets like that of the BIS – where for every pound you invest you get a multiple return in growth and tax receipts to the exchequer – is an utterly false economy,” he said.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/occams-corner/2015/sep/14/five-years-reasons-angry-science-funding-budget-cuts\">Science is vital: five reasons to be angry about science funding</a> </p> </aside>  <p>“So, as he puts the finishing touches to his comprehensive spending review, I say this to the chancellor: don’t cut off your nose to spite your face because it will be our economy which suffers.”</p> <p>The BIS, which has a resource budget of about £13bn, is under pressure to make savings of up to 40% over the next five years as part of a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/09/spending-review-how-the-cuts-could-fall-at-government-departments\">spending review to be announced by George Osborne</a> on 25 November. A <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.resolutionfoundation.org/publications/shrinking-pains-the-size-and-functions-of-the-state-over-the-parliament-and-beyond/\">report by the Resolution Foundation</a> thinktank estimated that the department’s total spending would fall by 53% between 2010 and 2020 under austerity measures planned by the Treasury. </p> <p>The bulk of the savings in the BIS budget since 2010 were made from shifting the burden of university funding to students under the £9,000 a year loan scheme. In 2015-16, the last year of the current spending round, the department must find another £450m in cuts, with only £150m to come from the universities’ teaching grant.</p> <p>Umunna said: “In order to drive forward the different elements of industrial strategy I’ve outlined, you need a strong business department, which is a powerhouse and the engine room of government. But in the last parliament the BIS budget was cut by 32% and is projected to have been cut by 53% by end of this one.”</p> <p>In the run-up to the spending review, which covers 2016-20, the business secretary, Sajid Javid, commissioned the management consultants McKinsey to examine the impact of merging or slimming the various bodies used by the department to dispense funds, including <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/political-science/2015/jul/27/in-defence-of-the-ref\">the higher education research councils</a>. </p> <p>But the level of savings needed to meet Treasury targets is expected to force Javid to make <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/occams-corner/2015/sep/14/five-years-reasons-angry-science-funding-budget-cuts\">cuts to science grants</a> and possibly abolish the BIS and merging its responsibilities with the education department and the Treasury.</p> <p>The BIS is the brainchild of Peter Mandelson, who in 2009 merged the Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform with the two-year old Department for Innovation, Universities and Skills.<br