tograph: Suzanne Plunkett/Reuters","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41/0_0_3228_1937/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41/0_0_3228_1937/3228.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41","suppliersReference":"SLP108","altText":"Mike Coupe","source":"Reuters","mediaId":"957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Suzanne Plunkett","credit":"Photograph: Suzanne Plunkett/Reuters","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41/0_0_3228_1937/3228.jpg","width":"3228","height":"1937"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41/0_0_3228_1937/master/3228.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41","suppliersReference":"SLP108","altText":"Mike Coupe","source":"Reuters","mediaId":"957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41","displayCredit":"true","photographer":"Suzanne Plunkett","credit":"Photograph: Suzanne Plunkett/Reuters","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/957541e52fe6c5df0f74dc44f37107e5aff2eb41/0_0_3228_1937/master/3228.jpg","width":"3228","height":"1937","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/financial3","webTitle":"Financial","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/financial3","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/financial3","sectionName":"Business"}]},{"id":"commentisfree/2015/nov/11/laundry-ninjas-free-market-science","type":"article","sectionId":"commentisfree","webTitle":"Never mind pointless apps – our best minds should be solving real problems | Helen Lewis","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T18:16:22Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1127","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e5e3","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"76204d1c759d886a3353b71457d5e7b554bfce93\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447268014812/6a5f0e98-febb-489b-a64d-012f8e9e2933-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Illustration by Ellie Foreman-Peck\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447268015252/7616bb97-2a4f-4218-8e53-b13aceb330da-140x84.jpeg","body":"<p>It all started with the snacks. A few months ago I lied to myself that eating “omega booster seeds” or tiny squares of carrot cake was in some way a substitute for nipping out to get a packet of Fruit Gums from the corner shop, and signed up to get “nibbles” delivered directly to my desk.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/aug/08/science-research-grants-awarded-on-the-basis-of-patents-is-patently-wrong\">Science research grants awarded on the basis of patents is patently wrong | Kim Carr</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Of course, that was just a gateway drug. Now there are days when my desk resembles a bustling village post office in the run-up to Christmas. And once you’ve been identified as sitting at the correct intersection of laziness and disposable income, you get a terrifying insight into quite how many things people want to send to your desk. A shirt in a box for when you’ve spilled your morning latte, or slept in a hedge. Artisan coffee in a box. Craft beer in a box. A “hug in a box”. Gwyneth Paltrow’s head in a box. (No, wait, that’s the end of the movie <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2012/nov/07/clip-joint-moral-dilemmas\" title=\"\">Se7en</a>).</p> <p>Even Uber is at it. Not content with winding up black-cab drivers, the posh minicab app has branched out into, essentially, <a href=\"http://money.cnn.com/2013/10/29/technology/uber-kittens/index.html\" title=\"\">kitten pimping</a>: in certain cities in the US and Australia it will deliver cats to your desk between noon and 4pm for 15 minutes of “snuggle time”. (Every fibre of my being says this must be a PR stunt rather than a genuine offer, but feel free to send me pictures of Uber-ordered kittens to prove me wrong. Or indeed any pictures of kittens. I like kittens.)</p> <p>The nadir came when I got a flyer advertising a monthly <a href=\"https://www.pinkparcel.co.uk/\" title=\"\">“pink parcel”</a> I could have delivered to my desk. Yes, that’s right, ladies – leave your co-workers in suspense no longer about why you’re such a mardy cow! For just £7.95 you can let them know that your period is due in three to five days with the arrival of a hamper full of tea bags, beauty products and sweets, plus tampons and sanitary towels. “A cup of tea solves everything!” boasts the Pink Parcel website. (I hear a particularly fragrant Earl Grey has just been appointed Middle East peace envoy, so expect good news from Gaza any time now.)</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>There are clearly not many people who wish to pay £7.95 to avoid a trip to Boots for a pack of Always Ultra</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>This stuff-in-a-box madness is an offshoot of a larger trend in start-up culture: pandering to middle-class urban professionals who value their time more highly than their disposable income. America, being America, has more eye-watering examples: in Washington DC, <a href=\"https://www.fetchcoffee.com/\" title=\"\">Fetch Coffee</a> will pick up your Starbucks order and, for $3, deliver it to your door before 8am. In big cities <a href=\"http://www.getwashio.com/\" title=\"\">Washio</a> will pick up and return your dry cleaning within 24 hours.</p> <p>Its decision to refer to its workers as “ninjas” makes the website FAQs feel totally surreal. “To be a ninja, you must have a valid in-state driver’s licence, current registration and insurance, a smartphone, and a 2000 model or newer vehicle,” it trills, mentioning nothing about wearing black or killing people with big swords. Often the names of these <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\" title=\"\">“disruptive” companies</a> are similarly parody-proof, as the dwindling number of available domain names leads to tortured misspellings. Thus, Britain’s answer to “<a href=\"https://www.shyp.com/\" title=\"\">Shyp</a>” (a delivery company) is called “<a href=\"http://weengs.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Weengs</a>”.</p> <p>The biggest problem with the world these companies envisage is that it doesn’t, and never will, exist. Tech start-ups are obsessed with scale, and there are clearly not that many people who have the ability or desire to pay $3 to have a cup of coffee delivered, or £7.95 to avoid a trip to Boots for a pack of Always Ultra.</p> <p>The next issue is that the imagined consumers are partly a reflection of the kind of people who launch a new app or online service: young, well-educated, often from a comfortable family background, and living in one of a handful of cities such as London or San Francisco. In a Vanity Fair article <a href=\"http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2015/08/is-silicon-valley-in-another-bubble\" title=\"\">asking whether Silicon Valley was in another tech bubble</a>, Nick Bilton quoted an overheard comment that sums up this mindset: “SF tech culture is focused on solving one problem: what is my mother no longer doing for me?”</p> <p>Many of these companies will fail, but here’s the real tragedy: the time and talent wasted on problems that aren’t really problems at all. There is something demented about such a huge flowering of creativity and innovation being focused on the minor inconveniences of the cash-rich and time-poor.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/nov/01/science-is-vital-british-legacy-contact-mp\">Science is vital if Britain is to prosper – make sure your MP knows that</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Out there is someone with an idea for an app that would revolutionise elderly care, or an online service that could smooth the life of a low-paid single parent. But those ideas might never even fully form before being dismissed; and they would struggle to attract the buzz and venture capital needed to mature into something truly world-changing. Even the most ardent free-marketeer (and there are plenty of those in Silicon Valley) must acknowledge that there are few commercial incentives to innovate on behalf of those who need it most.</p> <p>That’s where the state comes in. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/mazzucato-mariana\" title=\"\">Mariana Mazzucato</a>, one of the economists recently hired to advise Jeremy Corbyn, has a neat line: <a href=\"http://marianamazzucato.com/\" title=\"\">she points out that</a> every major component in the iPhone – Siri, GPS, the touchscreen – exists only because of publicly funded research. So don’t believe Silicon Valley superstars who tell us that they are the only innovators.</p> <p>This is not what the chancellor, George Osborne, wants to hear, of course. As part of his mission to roll back the state, science funding has been frozen since 2010 (meaning a real-terms cut of 6%). Britain now devotes just 1.7% of its GDP to research and development funding – behind the United States (2.8%) and Germany (2.9%), and the European Union target of 3%. There are facilities, built with taxpayers’ money, that we can no longer afford to run – the £400m neutron source in Harwell <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-34749609\" title=\"\">can only operate for 120 days a year, for example</a>.</p> <p>Last week the Commons science and technology committee warned that without more investment and the adoption of the 3% target, Britain will fall behind its competitors. “The UK risks losing its status as a world leader in research if the Treasury does not make a long-term commitment to increase science funding,” <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/news-parliament-2015/the-science-budget-report-published-15-16/\" title=\"\">said the committee chair, Nicola Blackwood</a>.</p> <p>This might all sound too dry to care about – God knows, any mention of EU targets always makes my eyes glaze over – but it’s important to our future. We can either encourage innovation and research to benefit everyone, by properly funding our science sector. Or we can leave it to the market, and get more laundry ninjas, more companies called things like Coffeeee and undrPants, and most of all, more bloody boxes sent to my desk.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10969982","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405352","internalRevision":"88","internalContentCode":"458368959","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"A huge flowering of creativity is focused on the minor inconveniences of the cash-rich and time-poor. That’s why we need proper funding for science","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Never mind pointless apps – our best minds should be solving real problems","byline":"Helen Lewis","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T18:16:22Z","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/11/1447268015252/7616bb97-2a4f-4218-8e53-b13aceb330da-140x84.jpeg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"56434ea8e4b091de41c2c08b","newspaperPageNumber":"45","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-14T18:16:22Z","standfirst":"<p>A huge flowering of creativity is focused on the minor inconveniences of the