pg\" alt=\"David Cameron \" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">David Cameron said he would be happy to ‘initiate dialogue’ with No 10 policy unit.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Ben Pruchnie/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/48cdb2f958a4b99d09de2d2e98754fc19f10dcc2/161_794_2192_1317/140.jpg","body":"<p>David Cameron has been accused of offering a Conservative council chief special access to No 10 advisers as a way to resolve a disagreement about proposed budget cuts.</p> <p>The prime minister is facing questions about his conduct after he wrote to Ian Hudspeth, the leader of Oxfordshire county council, chastising him for considering cuts to day centres, libraries and museums. Cameron’s own constituency of Witney falls within the area.</p> <p>In the letter, Cameron extended an offer for how to help to manage the cuts, saying he would be happy to “initiate a dialogue” with the No 10 policy unit about the possibilities of devolution deals and suggesting that Hudspeth contact his aide Sheridan Westlake, who used to work in the Department for Communities and Local Government.</p> <p>The intervention sparked <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/11/david-cameron-letter-cuts-oxfordshire\">accusations of hypocrisy</a> after the leaked letter showed Cameron criticising Hudspeth for considering cuts to local services. Hudspeth responded by taking issue with Cameron’s argument point by point, noting that central government funding had fallen dramatically. The exchange was <a href=\"http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/13948252.David_Cameron_clashes_with_council_over_cuts_to_frontline_services/\">obtained by the Oxford Mail</a>.</p> <p>Hudspeth told Cameron that the council had already cut back-office functions and looked at shared services as far back as 2006, reduced staff numbers by thousands and disposed of property. He pointed out new functions that had transferred to the council, including public health and social care.</p> <p>“Excluding schools, our total government grants have fallen from £194m in 2009/10 to £122m a year in 2015/16, and are projected to keep falling at a similar rate. I cannot accept your description of a drop in funding of £72m or 37% as a ‘slight fall’,” he wrote. Hudspeth also said he had “worked hard to assist you in achieving a Conservative majority”.</p> <p>Jon Ashworth, a shadow Cabinet Office minister, has written to the civil service chief Sir Jeremy Heywood asking for advice on the propriety of Cameron offering extra help for Oxfordshire.<br /></p> <p>He points out that the letter appears to have been written by the prime minister in his role as a Witney MP, even though the ministerial code states that he must keep separate his government and constituency role.</p> <p>“Is it the case that if the prime minister has made this offer of ‘further dialogue’ available to the leader of his local county council, similar offers should be made to all the leaders of other councils? Surely the leader of the prime minister’s county council should not be given preferential treatment?” Ashworth writes.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/11/david-cameron-letter-cuts-oxfordshire\">David Cameron hasn’t the faintest idea how deep his cuts go. This letter proves it | George Monbiot</a> </p> </aside>  <p>He asks for confirmation of whether the proposed meeting between Hudspeth and the policy unit has taken place and whether similar offers have been made to other council leaders.</p> <p>John McDonnell, the shadow chancellor, said the letter showed unbelievable hypocrisy. He said:<strong> “</strong>I’m backing David Cameron on this one. He is absolutely right that his chancellor’s cuts to local government are seriously damaging our communities and have to be opposed. I welcome the prime minister as another Tory MP joining our campaign against George Osborne’s cuts.”</p> <p>A spokesman for Cameron said: “There is still significant scope for sensible savings across local government to be made by back-office consolidation, disposing of surplus property and joining up our local public services; we will be discussing with Oxfordshire how this can be taken forward to help protect frontline services.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10971552","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-12T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2405528","internalRevision":"752","internalContentCode":"458370759","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Prime minister’s conduct questioned after he wrote to Ian Hudspeth criticising planned cuts","allowUgc":"false","headline":"David Cameron 'offered Oxfordshire council leader access to advisers'","byline":"Rowena Mason","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-11T18:40:00Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/48cdb2f958a4b99d09de2d2e98754fc19f10dcc2/161_794_2192_1317/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"5643772ce4b05f01ec0a2d7b","newspaperPageNumber":"9","standfirst":"<p>Prime minister’s conduct questioned after he wrote to Ian Hudspeth criticising planned cuts</p>","creationDate":"2015-11-11T17:13:16Z","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-12T08:56:54.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/11/david-cameron-offered-oxfordshire-council-leader-access-to-advisers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2015/nov/11/david-cameron-offered-oxfordshire-council-leader-access-to-advisers","sectionName":"Politics","elements":[{"id":"48cdb2f958a4b99d09de2d2e98754fc19f10dcc2","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/48cdb2f958a4b99d09de2d2e98754fc1