 at Goodwood on Reel Buddy in 2003.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Pat Eddery after winning the Sussex Stakes at Goodwood on Reel Buddy in 2003. Photograph: Chris Ison/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/10/1447156722693/Pat-Eddery-after-winning--001.jpg","body":"<p>Pat Eddery, who has died aged 63 after a long period of ill health, was the second most successful jockey in the history of British horseracing in terms of the number of winners ridden. Between 1969 and 2003 he rode 4,632 winners in Britain – a total exceeded only by <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/content/articles/2005/03/18/sport_heroes_gordon_richards_feature.shtml\">Gordon Richards</a>, with 4,870 ridden between 1921 and 1954. Third in the all-time list in Britain is Lester Piggott, with 4,493 winners. While he could not match Piggott for taciturnity, like his great rival Eddery was a shy, withdrawn sportsman who disliked the limelight.</p> <p>His 14 classic victories in Britain include the Derby three times; he was champion flat jockey in Britain 11 times – the same total as Piggott – and champion on the flat in Ireland in 1982. The first of Eddery’s many winners came on Alvaro at Epsom in April 1969, and less than two months later Eddery won his first major prize, on Sky Rocket in the Wokingham Stakes at Royal Ascot.</p> <p>He finished the 1971 season as champion apprentice with 71 winners, and in 1972 had his first Derby ride – the 50-1 chance Pentland Firth, who finished third behind Roberto and Rheingold – and his first victory in a Group 1 race: Erimo Hawk, awarded the Gold Cup at Ascot on the disqualification of Rock Roi for interference.</p> <p>Despite losing out on that occasion, Rock Roi’s trainer, <a href=\"http://www.lambourntraining.org/trainers/peter-walwyn-chairman-of-the-lta\">Peter Walwyn</a>, had been impressed by the Irishman’s unfussy riding style, and towards the end of the 1972 term offered Eddery the position of stable jockey at what was then one of the most important yards in racing. The arrangement soon brought big-race success. In 1973 Eddery, still only 21, was top jockey at Royal Ascot, while 1974 saw his first winner of an English classic – Polygamy in the Oaks – and his first jockeys’ championship, with 148 winners.</p> <p>Four of those wins came on the Walwyn-trained, two-year-old Grundy, which the following year became the first great horse of Eddery’s career. Though beaten in the 2,000 Guineas, Grundy won the Irish equivalent before producing a brilliant performance to land the Derby decisively.</p> <p>Following victory in the Irish Derby, Grundy and Eddery headed for the King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Diamond Stakes at Ascot, where an exceptionally high-class field included the five-year-old mare Dahlia, which had won the King George in 1973 and 1974, and the four-year-old Bustino, winner of the St Leger in 1974 and the Coronation Cup earlier in the 1975 season. After a furious pace had been set through the first mile, the race boiled down to a head-to-head duel up the straight between Grundy and Bustino, with the younger horse winning by half a length after a battle that swiftly – and justifiably – became known as “the race of the century”.</p> <p>Eddery remained as stable jockey to Walwyn for eight years, before joining the Irish trainer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/jun/02/obituary-vincent-obrien\">Vincent O’Brien</a>, for whom he rode a string of big-race winners, including Golden Fleece, owned by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/apr/09/guardianobituaries.horseracing\">Robert Sangster</a>, in the 1982 Derby.</p> <p>But the same owner–trainer–jockey combination experienced controversial defeat in the Derby two years later, when the unbeaten 2,000 Guineas winner El Gran Senor seemed to be cruising to victory in the final furlong, only to be caught on the line by Secreto, trained by O’Brien’s son David, and beaten by a short head. Eddery was widely criticised by riders in the stand, but insisted that his mount had simply reached the limit of his stamina in the final hundred yards.</p> <p>Happier landmarks in the 1980s included winning the 1983 Arlington Million in Chicago on Tolomeo; the 1985 Breeders’ Cup Turf at <a href=\"https://www.nyra.com/aqueduct/information/history-aqueduct/\">Aqueduct</a>, New York, on Pebbles, trained by Clive Brittain, the first British success in a Breeders’ Cup race; and the 1986 Japan Cup on Jupiter Island, also trained by Brittain.</p> <p>The same decade gave Eddery four victories in the Prix de l’Arc de Triomphe: on Detroit in 1980, Rainbow Quest in 1985, the great Dancing Brave – on whom he also won the King George – in 1986, and Trempolino in 1987.</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XnGVCjU_Qa0\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/XnGVCjU_Qa0?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption>Pat Eddery storms to victor on Dancing Brave in 1986</figcaption> </figure>   <p>Rainbow Quest and Dancing Brave were both owned by the Saudi Prince Khalid Abdullah, whose <a href=\"http://www.juddmonte.com\">Juddmonte Farms</a> is one of the world’s largest racing and breeding organisations, and in 1987 Eddery became Abdullah’s retained jockey. Highlights of their association, which lasted until 1994, included Quest for Fame winning the 1990 Derby and Zafonic the 1993 2,000 Guineas. Meanwhile, Eddery continued to clock up the jockeys’ championships. His highest seasonal total was 209 in 1990 – the first time a jockey had exceeded 200 since Richards in 1952 – and he was champion for the 11th and final time in 1996.</p> <p>Eddery was born in Dublin and brought up in Newbridge, County Kildare, the fifth of 12 children of Jimmy and Josephine Eddery. Both Jimmy, and Pat’s maternal grandfather, Jack Moylan, were prominent riders – they dead-heated for the Irish 2,000 Guineas in 1944 – and his father finished second in the 1955 Derby on Panaslipper, before winning the Irish Derby on the same horse.</p> <p>At the age of eight, Pat started riding racehorses at the yard of the trainer Seamus McGrath, near Leopardstown racecourse. “I had no fear of horses, even at that age when I was dwarfed by them,” he recalled in his 1992 autobiography, To Be a Champion, “and on horseback I was instilled with a conviction and self-belief I never felt at other times.”</p> <p>On his 14th birthday he was formally apprenticed to McGrath. In his first ride in public he finished last, and he did not win a race until moving to England to complete his apprenticeship with the trainer Herbert “Frenchie” Nicholson, famous for his tutelage of young jockeys.</p> <p>He retired from riding in 2003, and in 2005 took out a licence to train at Musk Hill Stud in Buckinghamshire: Visionist at Kempton Park in April 2006 was his first winner in this new role. But his training career was never in the same league as his riding – his sole Group 1 victory came with Hearts of Fire in the 2009 Gran Criterium at San Siro, Milan – and reached a well-publicised low when Eddery was sued for unfair dismissal by his brother Paul, who had been helping out at Musk Hill. The claim was dismissed.</p> <p>Pat, who was appointed an honorary OBE in 2005, married Carolyn Mercer, the daughter of the flat jockey Manny Mercer, in 1978. They divorced in 2009.</p> <p>He is survived by their two daughters, Nichola, an equestrian artist, and Natasha, and a son, Harry.</p> <p>• Patrick James John Eddery, jockey and racehorse trainer, born 18 March 1952; died 10 November 2015</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10965996","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate